##A book of reflection from neighboring South Korea: Biographies Of Victims, not numbers

Feature description, a short original video every day, every day to tell a moving story, every day selected human beauty, every day to live a better life with me.

12 died.

In less than a week, South Korea's new crown disease broke out in a blowout,

In the city of Daegu, where the epidemic is most severe,

Locals lined up for thousands of meters to buy masks.

Looking back five years,

May-july 2015,

Middle East Respiratory Syndrome has swept South Korea,

A total of 186 confirmed cases, resulting in 38 deaths,

Forced the closure of thousands of primary and secondary schools.

Kim Tak-hwan, a South Korean writer, uses MERS victims as a backdrop for his fiction

The number of confirmed cases, the mortality rate,

The economic impact, the panic,

South Korea's Kim Tak-hwan sees one helpless patient after another,

They don't have names, they don't dare reveal their identities,

All that's left is the serial number:

Patient one, patient two..

So he took the Mers case as a source,

He wrote a nonfiction novel

I want to live: The people in the MERS storm

"I have always believed that literature should stand

The poor, the weak and the injured.

Not just literature, but all of us."

In early January this year, a Chinese translation of the book was published,

An interview with Kim Tak-hwan,

From Mers to new coronavirus pneumonia,

Why does it always happen again and again?

Before saying, "never forget, always remember, "

We need to know what to remember,

People, not numbers, must be found.

Kim Tak-hwan, editor

Kim Tak-hwan cared about social issues and spoke for the disadvantaged through his writing

Born in 1968, Korean writer Kim Tak-hwan is known as "the author of the new Korean historical novel. " . He is good at taking the real person in the society as the prototype, creates the on-the-spot novel. He has written twice based on "the sinking of the SEWOL in Korea in 2014" , and several novels including "Immortal Admiral Yi Sun-sin" and "Hwang Jini" have been transformed into films and TV series.

In 2016, he began work on his novel I'm going to live: The people in the Mers Storm, set among the victims of the virus. In addition to collecting tons of material and checking up on news reports, he also visits the patients, families, and doctors who experienced Mers, and in the novel Recounts Their Plight, the atmosphere of the society at the time, and reflects on who was responsible?

When the Chinese translation of I will live: The people in the Mers storm was published in January 2020, it coincided with the global spread of the new coronavirus. Kim Tak-hwan was scheduled to appear at the Taipei Book Fair on Feb. 7 for a team interview, but the event was postponed due to the outbreak, so we went by email instead.

From MERS in 2015 to new pneumonia in 2020, has society done better in the face of a pandemic?

Here's Kim Tak-hwan's account.

Photograph: Kim  

The epidemic is over, but life goes on.

I wanted to write a novel about the Mers incident in late spring of 2016. It has been a year since the epidemic, known as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome, swept the Korean Peninsula in May 2015. While many MERS victims were reluctant to be interviewed, I managed to get in touch with a few people who were still reluctant to meet with reporters, even as they wept bitterly about how MERS had ruined their lives.

They say there is nothing to hide if one goes on a flesh search -- no one wants to be labeled a MERS patient again.

As I reviewed news and television programs related to Mers in 2015, there was so much about governments, local governments and hospital staff that there were so few stories about MERS victims. If it did, it was mostly about what happened in the isolation ward after it was coded in the order it was diagnosed.

They are free individuals, members of a social community, whose past, present and future we do not see in our reports.

A biography of the victim:

They want to be remembered as individuals

So I started writing about the victims. Before we say "never forget, always remember" , we need to know what to remember, and we need to retrieve "people" , not "numbers" . With a lot of help, I met with the victim.

I'm grateful to those I've met and those I haven't, and I understand the mixed feelings and realities of those who, so far, haven't formally formed a community of Mers victims. People are divided narrowly into normal and abnormal, and those who are divided into abnormal are labeled and loathed over and over again.

Because of this, I find it difficult to write a documentary directly with real people, events and backgrounds. Although I changed the settings of the people I met, I still wanted to write about their pain, sometimes it was sigh, sometimes it was tears, sometimes it was cry, sometimes it was struggle, sometimes it was silence!

I stared at them for hours, listened to them, read together, and went on field trips. The process makes people feel sad, "if this is not hell, where is hell? " , "that hell is still ongoing" ... These words and sighs, deeply hurt my heart.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: AP

The people who "got MERS, "

And the life you can't bear to see

Huge, cold walls were exposed.

The state and hospitals do not admit mistakes, because they do not admit, so there is no compensation and compensation, this way to lose everything because of infectious diseases how cruel. The vast majority of victims have no medical expertise, many have never been to court in their lives and know nothing about the law.

Survivors and survivors who pour out their grievances do not remember what treatment they received in the isolation ward, when the patient's condition began to deteriorate or deteriorate to what extent. They only remember a good person in just 10 days, half a month, constantly struggling in the death line, the process is not clear, which let them fall into deep despair.

Life and death can not be left to chance. It would be shallow and foolish to think you were "lucky" just because you weren't infected, just because you weren't on that boat. Moreover, it is not the sense of community to reject those in dire straits rather than to lend a helping hand.

The Films Saving Private Ryan and the Martian are touching precisely because the social community does not give up on the individual, and does not measure its worth in terms of economic loss and the likelihood of success.

We did not guard the victims, did not prevent the criticism of the isolators, and even tried to turn the victims into the perpetrators, the "super disseminator" is a typical example. Victims of sudden infectious disease, just to fight the disease has been unable to do, those rumors, but also hurt them Bug.

We did not activate the social safety net. There was no explanation for the failure of society to do its best to help those who had lost loved ones to Mers and who had barely recovered, and why their loved ones had been infected and left the world, there are no policies to help people who have been forced to lose their jobs, and there are no policies to actively treat the trauma of those people.

They hoped to return to normal life after recovery, but "infected MERS" ruined their long life later, can not bear to see.

Falling, falling, falling day after day! But there was no net anywhere to stop the fall.

From Mers to the new coronavirus:

I firmly believe that literature should stand on the side of the weak and hurt

On September 8,2018, there was another confirmed case of Mers in South Korea.

Although I expected the epidemic to reappear, I did not expect it to reappear three years later when I was working on the novel. Fortunately, the initial response and prevention was very successful.

After the news broadcast that day, I got a call from the first MERS victim. They sobbed and asked me, why did prevention work now, but not three years ago? If the name of the hospital were made public right now, like this time, there would be no loss of family.

The "failure" of prevention and treatment has killed and injured many people, who are being reported to the state and hospitals. They had to leave their homes, move to new places, and pay for therapy. Although these people's life appearance are all different, actually all still lives in the pain. We can't look at this as a personal tragedy. While 2015 may not have been a time to focus on those who are suffering in the dark abyss, at least it's now time to embrace and care for them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Kim Tak-hwan has been in contact with MERS patients she visited

From my first publication of the novel 22 years ago, I have always believed that literature should be on the side of the poor, the weak and the injured.

This time, right now, the COVID-19 is attacking the world, including South Korea. See South Korean people because of the outbreak launched "ban Chinese" appeal news, ignorance will magnify fear, magnify fear will extend to hate. We should not have this kind of hatred to blame infected people, infected areas, infected countries.

Photograph: Ed Jonesgetty Images

The most important thing now is for countries to share information in a timely manner and to use that information as a basis for informed and effective responses.

I also believe that the South Korean government, in order not to repeat the past, is doing its utmost to prevent COVID-19.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: Ahn young-joonap

On May 20,2015, at 11:00 am, three epidemiological investigators arrived at the 8th floor of the W hospital in Gyeonggi Province, Seoul. Dressed in Class C protective gear, they entered the ward in sequence, and the epidemiological investigation was treated as a secret.

Investigators, wearing double gloves inside and outside, carefully examined the bed, window frames, the ceiling, not a hair was spared, everything was sealed in plastic bags. Just then, a ray of sunlight came in, making the white cowl, Yellow Hazmat suit and blue apron even more vivid. On this Earth, this outfit is not welcome anywhere.

It was the opening act of a nonfiction novel, I'm going to live: The people in the MERS storm. South Korean ward investigated after Mers patient No. 1 emerged in 2015.

In 2015, when the Middle East Respiratory Syndrome virus spread from the Middle East to the rest of the world, South Korea became the world's fastest infected country after Saudi Arabia. Between May and July of that year, South Korea had 186 confirmed cases and 38 deaths, with a mortality rate of more than 20 percent.

The cover-up seemed to be the beginning of all outbreaks.

In fact, the first case of Mers in South Korea was confirmed on May 20, but as early as May 12, this "patient 1" was treated in three hospitals, and it was not until the fourth hospital that he was found to have visited Bahrain in the Middle East, it's a highly probable MERS case. The hospital immediately reported the case, but the Korean Center for Disease Control and Prevention refused to confirm the diagnosis, so the patient was put on hold for another 36 hours. On May 27, the virus was transmitted to 14 people who were also in the emergency room at the time, and the epidemic began to spread..

Kim Tak-hwan begins with the hospital, and the three main characters in the novel, it was among the 14 people infected with Mers in the emergency room: Jin Shizhu, a dentist who had just returned from a treatment for lymphoma; Lee Il-hwa, a journalist intern who had seen off her terminally ill father; and Ji Donghua, a storekeeper who ran a business. Three people were diagnosed with Mers, and their lives changed.

Unwittingly passing the disease on to relatives,

Am I a perpetrator?

Lee Il-hwa had just graduated from college and was working as an intern at a news station. On May 27, she accompanied her terminally ill father to the emergency room, where he died, unaware that he had contracted Mers in the process.

"there are important moments in life that we rarely get a chance to know in advance, " he said. At his father's funeral on May 28-30, nearly all of his relatives showed up, and the family gathered to comfort each other.

When I got home, I slept until the middle of the night. For five months as a trainee journalist, the pace of work was fast, and I ran all day and all night without a good rest. When she got up, she felt her earlobe burning, as if she had a low-grade fever, and her head was dizzy. Until June 4, when he developed a high fever and cough that lasted until early morning.

On June 1, one of the senior journalists received a need for secrecy: one of the patients who reportedly visited the emergency room of F hospital from May 27 to 29 was diagnosed with Mers on May 30. By the morning of June 4, government press releases were trickling into reporters'mailboxes: It's Mers.

Colleagues just reflected the situation of a flower: "compared to the interview, to Save People Ah! " 4 at 11 pm, the ambulance sent a flower from home to the hospital, 6,7 twice tested positive, a flower confirmed infection MERS.

Fortunately, Yihua was young and resistant, and was discharged from the hospital within two weeks. That's when she learned that four of her relatives had been infected with Mers at the funeral, including an uncle who had died. "Is it wrong for a family to be on good terms? "

In media reports, a flower to see a line of notes "these victims, because infected with the virus, but became the perpetrators" , highly infectious patients are also called "super-disseminators. She couldn't bear the pain: How could it be so simple to distinguish between the victim and the perpetrator? So Am I the perpetrator? Shouldn't we first think about the rigid system of hospitals that infect patients and spread the virus?"

After recovery from the hospital, why it seems to be abandoned by the world?

Also in the emergency room that day was Ji Donghua, who had worked in the publishing industry for 30 years.

At 50, she raised her college aged son on her own and took care of her younger sister, who was 15 years apart. Fortunately, she was the first patient transferred to the Mers Ward and was transferred to a regular ward in just four days.

I thought I could go back to the society after I was cured and my life was back to normal. I didn't think everything was too naive. Here's the reality: You can't take the Mers tag off your body. After leaving the hospital, she showered four or five times a day, fearing that she would bring bad luck. But as she walked out the door, neighbors she had known for more than 10 years began to duck.

Photograph: Chung sung-jungetty Images

Dong Hua loses half of the lung function in the course of treatment, weight lost 20 kilograms, could have put 20 books on the back of the body, but now there is no way, accidentally cough, colleagues all scared far away.

Because of her diagnosis, the company has reduced the volume of shipments, many publishers asked to change the warehouse, because she felt dirty also dare not touch her books, she held back tears, explained to the boss: "I have recovered, the doctor said there will be no recurrence. "

The boss said: "not to kill you, so that the company can live. "

In this way, Dong Hua was abandoned by the company and Industry that had worked for 30 years. "people all over the world say I'm dirty. How the hell am I supposed to prove I'm clean? "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The last patient to be "erased" :

Who's responsible for the broken family?

Compared with Lee Il-hwa and Ji Donghua, the situation of Jinshizhu is more complicated.

Shi Zhu, 37, works in a dentist's office, lives happily with his wife, Yingya, and has a 5 year old son. Of the three people in the emergency room on May 27, the first to return to the hospital was Jin Shizhu, because he was a lymphoma patient. Early on the morning of June 1st, he went to the hospital to see his cancer doctor. Turns out, he was also the last MERS case.

As a result of the basic disease of Lymphoma, leading to his repeated illness, the virus test negative, positive alternate. All the other patients were discharged within two weeks, and in the end, he was alone.

According to the official "Daily News" , there have been no confirmed cases for 23 days since July 4. On July 28th, as if waiting for that day, South Korea's prime minister declared to the world that the MERS outbreak was over and that South Korea was no longer an epidemic.

Picture. Photograph: Chung sung-jungetty Images

At this time, Jin Shizhu is still a man, fighting in the ward. The estranged wife, unable to see her husband, was heartbroken, angry and helpless: "My husband endured hell and death for Mers, and the government was in a hurry to erase the word Mers. Who is responsible for our family's misfortune and pain? "

Because Mers was once again sent to the negative pressure isolation ward of the stone column, the cancer has been delayed treatment. The ball is in the court: Hospitals are putting medical decisions on the government, and the government on the WHO, whose advice is not to respond to immediate needs.

"I was locked in there, on the edge of life and death, and the world went on as before. One suffers, one dies, and even if one dies, it is not my name that is left behind, but the government-coded number 'patient 38. ' "

From June to November, after several ITERATIONS, the golden pillar of "I will live" could not hold.

"Jin Shi Zhu, dead. Time of death is 3:06 on November 25. "

Editorial afterword

It is, so to speak, a book of reflection from neighbouring South Korea.

The miscalculation of the first patient, the concealment of the list of hospitals where the outbreak of infection occurred, the omission of close contacts, the neglect of in-hospital protection, the lack of coordination among the various parts of the medical system, the substitution of victims for solutions... and after the epidemic has passed, what about the survivors, the Python patients?

The experience of the common victims of the storm, and the cost to the individual, is something that Kim Tak-hwan has been keenly aware of, and should be something that we all should be aware of.

Each of us is a member of the community. We should not just forget and distance ourselves. We should listen and comfort those who have been hurt by the epidemic. We should protect those who want to cry out, "I want to live. " Who were forced to be silent and fearful.

Pray for an early containment of the epidemic in South Korea and for more people to return to normal and positive lives.
